{meta: title Mister Joe Henry's Happy Hand Clappin'}
{meta: artist Charlie Pride}
{meta: composer Larry Lee and Glenn D. Tubb}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]Now Mister Joe Henry was a happy little man
Who [D7]became a legend in our [C]town
Most everybody owes a lot of the smiles  
To the [D7]happy sounds that he puts [G7]down
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
He had [C]one guitar and four other guys
Who [F]kept time with their clappin’ [C]hands
We call him [F]Mister Joe Henry’s [C]happy hand [D7]clappin’
[G7]Open air rhythm [C]band
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
Oh you can [G7]find ‘em every evening when the sun went down
At the [F]corner of fourth and [C]main
It [D7]didn’t take much of that hand clappin’ rhythm
To [G7]start the sun a-shinning again
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
I [C]can’t help but feel this part of the world
Is [F]supposed to do the good Lord’s [C]plan
Because of [F]Mister Joe Henry’s [C]happy hand [D7]clappin’
[G7]Open air rhythm [C]band
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
We’d all gather around and call out the names 
Of [D7]our favorite songs of the [C]day
But it didn’t much matter to mister Joe Henry
They [D7]all came out the same ol’ [G7]way
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
